#Task 7:Policy Brief: Making Backyards Affordable for All

#Primary Sponsor Metro: Burlington, NC Metro Area #Co-Sponsor Metro: Miami–Fort Lauderdale, FL Metro Area

##Housing affordability is a growing challenge across the U.S. Our analysis of ACS (2009–2023) and BLS QCEW data shows that metros that permit more housing experience lower rent burden and continued population growth, while low-building metros face rising rent pressure.

#What Our Metrics Mean

#Rent Burden Index (RBI) #Measures how much income households spend on rent.

#100 = U.S. baseline

#Higher = less affordable

#Burlington improved from 112 → 90.5

#Miami worsened from 136 → 144

#Housing Growth Composite (HG) #Measures how many homes are permitted relative to demand.

#100 = U.S. average

#Burlington: 102

#Miami: 35.8

#Evidence of YIMBY Success

#Burlington, NC:

#Rent burden dropped significantly (112 → 90.5)

#Population grew (+23,373 residents)

#Housing growth kept pace (HG = 102)

#This means homebuilding helped affordability.

#❌ When Housing Doesn’t Keep Up

#Miami–Fort Lauderdale:

#Rent burden worsened (136 → 144)

#Population grew +253,380

#Housing growth very low (HG = 35.8)

#High demand, insufficient supply → higher rents.

#👥 Who Benefits

#Health care workers (NAICS 62) #Large share of workforce in both metros — housing affordability improves staffing stability.

#Finance & insurance workers (NAICS 52) #Common in Florida and North Carolina — lower rent frees income for saving and spending, supporting the local economy.

Policy Proposal

#Create a Federal YIMBY Incentive Fund to:

#Reward metros demonstrating housing production tied to affordability gains

#Support high-burden metros in modernizing zoning & streamlining permitting

#Prioritize infill, duplex/quadplex, and mid-rise “missing middle” housing

#📌 Bottom Line

#Burlington shows building works. #Miami shows what happens when it doesn’t.

#Build more homes → lower rents → stronger workforce → thriving communities.

Report:

Housing Affordability & Growth Report

(ACS + Census Building Permits, 2009–2023)**

Executive Summary

This report analyzes U.S. housing affordability, population dynamics, and construction patterns from 2009–2023 using ACS 1-year estimates and Census building permits. We construct two custom indicators:

Rent Burden Index (RBI) (100 = baseline affordability; >100 = more burden) Measures how rent affordability changed over time.

Housing Growth Composite Index (HG) (100 = national average) Combines permitting per capita and permitting relative to population growth to identify “YIMBY metros” — regions building enough housing to meet demand.

Key Findings

Metros with higher permit activity experienced slower rent-burden growth or declines.

Metros with low housing supply response faced sharply rising rent burden.

Burlington, NC stands out as a YIMBY success — rising population with declining rent burden.

Miami-Fort Lauderdale represents housing supply failure — strong population inflows, but insufficient housing supply → rapidly worsening rent pressure.

Household size did not meaningfully increase, meaning overcrowding is not masking demand — supply truly fell behind in constrained markets.

Across metros, median rent remains tightly correlated with median income, indicating standard economic forces still dominate regional housing markets.

Data & Methods

Data Sources

ACS 1-year tables:

Income (B19013)

Rent (B25064)

Population (B01003)

Households (B11001)

Census Building Permits Survey (2009–2023)

BLS QCEW industry employment data (for workforce impact analysis)

Key Metrics Constructed

Rent Burden Index (RBI)

RBI=Median RentMedian Income×100 RBI= Median Income Median Rent ​

×100

Housing Growth Composite

Instant permits per capita

Permits relative to 5-year population growth

Standardized + averaged

YIMBY classification A metro is a “YIMBY success” if it: ✅ had high rent burden early ✅ reduced rent burden ✅ grew population ✅ built above the national average (Burlington, NC qualifies)

Visual Findings & Interpretation 1️⃣ Rent & Income Relationship (Scatterplot, 2009)

A clear positive correlation — higher income metros pay more rent. This validates economic housing theory and confirms ACS reliability.

2️⃣ Housing Permits Over Time (line plot)

We see a strong post-2011 recovery in permitting nationally, but uneven across regions.

Top builders: Houston, Dallas, NYC, Atlanta, DC Interpretation: Sun Belt and large metros have maintained strong supply pipelines.

3️⃣ Burlington vs Miami Housing Growth (3-panel time series) Metric Burlington, NC Miami–Fort Lauderdale Housing growth Consistent, near nat’l avg Volatile, often below demand Population Moderate growth Very high growth Rent burden Fell (112 → 90.5) Rose sharply (136 → 144)
